Implement context-sensitive Escape behavior.

**Spec Reference:** docs/CREATE_BEAD_SPEC.md Section 4.2 (Escape Hierarchy), Section 3.4-3.5 (Two-Stage Escape)

**Escape Hierarchy (Section 6 Keyboard Reference):**

| State | Esc Does |
|-------|----------|
| Parent dropdown open | Close search, revert to pre-search value |
| Parent focused (cleared/unchanged) | Revert pending change, move to Title |
| Labels dropdown open (1st Esc) | Close dropdown, keep typed text |
| Labels (2nd Esc) | Clear input, stay in field |
| Assignee dropdown open (1st Esc) | Close dropdown, keep typed text |
| Assignee (2nd Esc) | Revert to original value |
| Title / Other fields | Close entire modal |

**Key Principle (Section 10):** "Escape to safe state: Always possible. User never feels trapped."

**Implementation:**
```go
func (m *CreateOverlay) handleEscape() tea.Cmd {
    switch m.Focus {
    case FocusParent:
        if m.IsParentSearchActive {
            m.IsParentSearchActive = false
            m.ParentPending = m.ParentOriginal
            return nil
        }
        // Move to Title, revert any pending changes
        m.ParentID = m.ParentOriginal
        m.Focus = FocusTitle
        return nil
    case FocusLabels:
        if m.IsLabelsDropdownOpen {
            m.IsLabelsDropdownOpen = false
            return nil // Keep typed text (1st Esc)
        }
        if m.LabelsInput != "" {
            m.LabelsInput = "" // Clear input (2nd Esc)
            return nil
        }
        // Close modal
        return func() tea.Msg { return CreateCancelledMsg{} }
    case FocusAssignee:
        if m.IsAssigneeDropdownOpen {
            m.IsAssigneeDropdownOpen = false
            return nil // Keep typed text (1st Esc)
        }
        if m.AssigneeInput != m.AssigneeOriginal {
            m.AssigneeInput = ""
            m.SelectedAssignee = m.AssigneeOriginal
            return nil // Revert (2nd Esc)
        }
        return func() tea.Msg { return CreateCancelledMsg{} }
    default:
        return func() tea.Msg { return CreateCancelledMsg{} }
    }
}
```

**Testing:**
- Unit tests for each Escape scenario
- `./scripts/tui-test.sh` to verify:
  - Esc from Title closes modal
  - Esc from Labels dropdown keeps text
  - 2nd Esc from Labels clears text
  - Esc from Parent reverts and moves to Title

Add logic to resolve the `duplicate_of` and `superseded_by` issue fields into Node pointers after building the nodeMap.

## Background

Unlike other relationships stored in the dependencies table, `duplicate_of` and `superseded_by` are **issue-level fields**. When you run:
- `bd duplicate ab-123 --of ab-456` ‚Üí sets ab-123.duplicate_of = "ab-456"
- `bd supersede ab-old --with ab-new` ‚Üí sets ab-old.superseded_by = "ab-new"

These are string IDs in the issue JSON that need to be resolved to actual Node pointers for display.

## Implementation

In internal/graph/builder.go, after building nodeMap and processing dependencies:

```go
// Resolve graph link fields (duplicate_of, superseded_by)
for _, node := range nodeMap {
    if node.Issue.DuplicateOf != "" {
        if canonical, ok := nodeMap[node.Issue.DuplicateOf]; ok {
            node.DuplicateOf = canonical
        }
    }
    if node.Issue.SupersededBy != "" {
        if replacement, ok := nodeMap[node.Issue.SupersededBy]; ok {
            node.SupersededBy = replacement
        }
    }
}
```

## Edge Cases

**Referenced issue not in current view:**
If the canonical/replacement issue isn't loaded (filtered out, different status filter, etc.), the pointer stays nil. The detail view handles this gracefully by only rendering the section when the pointer is non-nil.

**Circular references:**
Theoretically impossible - an issue can't be marked as duplicate of itself (beads CLI prevents this), and the supersedes relationship creates a linear chain. But even if data was corrupted, the code is safe since we're just looking up by ID.

## Backward Compatibility

When parsing beads v0.0.30 data:
- `node.Issue.DuplicateOf` will be "" (empty string)
- `node.Issue.SupersededBy` will be "" (empty string)
- The if-checks ensure we skip resolution for empty strings
- No errors, no impact on existing functionality

## Task

Update CreateOverlay description field to use Slack-style keybindings:
- Enter = Submit form (even when in description field)
- Shift+Enter = Insert newline

## Files to Modify

- `internal/ui/overlay_create.go` - Key handling logic

## Implementation

### Key Handling (overlay_create.go)

Modify the KeyEnter handler around line 394-409:

Before:
```go
case tea.KeyEnter:
    if m.isCreating {
        return m, nil
    }
    // Ctrl+Enter always submits
    if msg.String() == "ctrl+enter" {
        return m.handleSubmit(true)
    }
    // Regular Enter submits if not in a dropdown and not in description
    if !m.isAnyDropdownOpen() && m.focus != FocusDescription && m.labelsCombo.combo.Value() == "" {
        return m.handleSubmit(false)
    }
```

After:
```go
case tea.KeyEnter:
    if m.isCreating {
        return m, nil
    }

    // In description field: Shift+Enter for newline, Enter for submit
    if m.focus == FocusDescription {
        if msg.String() == "shift+enter" {
            return m.handleZoneInput(msg)
        }
        return m.handleSubmit(false)
    }

    // Other fields: Enter submits if not in dropdown
    if !m.isAnyDropdownOpen() && m.labelsCombo.combo.Value() == "" {
        return m.handleSubmit(false)
    }
```

Note: This task does NOT remove bulk mode - that's a separate task.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Enter in description field submits form
- [ ] Shift+Enter in description field inserts newline
- [ ] Enter behavior unchanged for other fields (title, type, priority, etc.)
- [ ] Works in both Ghostty and iTerm2
